Project Execution Instructions
Step 0 – Download the Script

Download the project script file and save it in a local directory on your computer.

Step 1 – Install Python

Visit the official Python website:
https://www.python.org/downloads/

Download Python 3.11 or 3.12
During installation, it is very important to select the option:
	Add Python to PATH
Then click “Install Now”
Step 2 – Open Command Prompt

Open the command prompt (CMD) or terminal on your system.

Step 3 – Verify Python Installation

Run the following command to confirm that Python is correctly installed:

python -V
Step 4 – Navigate to the Project Folder

Use the command line to navigate to the directory where the script is located.

Step 5 – Create a Virtual Environment

Create a dedicated virtual environment for this project:

py -3.14 -m venv forex_env

Activate the virtual environment:

forex_env\Scripts\activate
Step 6 – Upgrade pip (Optional)

Update pip to the latest version:

python -m pip install --upgrade pip
Step 7 – Install Required Libraries

Install all necessary dependencies:

pip install yfinance pandas numpy matplotlib scikit-learn lightgbm fredapi
Step 8 – Run the Script

Once all libraries are installed, execute the script using:

python forex_predictionJoseOlmos.py
Step 9 – Deactivate the Virtual Environment (Optional)

After completing the execution, you can exit the virtual environment with:

deactivate


1. Source URLs of Original Data

The project uses data collected from two main APIs:

Financial Data (FOREX)
Source: Yahoo Finance
Accessed via: yfinance
URL: https://finance.yahoo.com/

Description:
Historical foreign exchange (FOREX) data for currency pairs (USD/CLP, USD/COP, USD/CAD) was retrieved programmatically using the Yahoo Finance API.

Macroeconomic Data
Source: Federal Reserve Economic Data
Accessed via: fredapi
URL: https://fred.stlouisfed.org/

Indicators used:

Federal Funds Rate (Interest Rate)
Crude Oil Prices
Consumer Price Index (CPI)

Description:
Macroeconomic indicators were obtained from the FRED database to enrich the model with external economic factors.

2. Modified Data Files
Description of Processed Data

The original datasets were transformed and combined into a structured dataset for machine learning purposes.

Key modifications include:

Merging datasets using the Date field (time series alignment)
Handling missing values using forward filling
Creating new features:
Technical indicators (SMA, RSI, MACD)
Volatility measures
Lag variables (previous day prices)
Returns (daily and weekly)
Final Dataset Characteristics
Total observations: 7,913 rows
Total features: 20 columns
Target variable: Next-day closing price (Close_next)
